From:		Randy Miskanic
Sent:		Tuesday, March 15, 2016 4:06 PM
To:		'Jared Isaacman'
Cc:		J.D. Oder II; Shel Kaplan
Subject		RE: Gemini

Jared,

Gemini is the project name of the solution for supporting American Express cards through the existing debit
networks. We also have an internal project name, "Amextra."

We delivered this capability on 2/2/16 for all Ingenico and Verifone PIN pads on First Data.

We began certifying lPads on TSYS last week. iPad support is lower priority because very few of our current
customers use them. The remaining PIN pads, which are Verifone and Ingenico on TSYS, are scheduled to
follow shortly after that (we anticipate in the next 30 days or so, although the schedule could be accelerated.)

The support for Amex cards on this new program is limited to those cards that are most commonly issued, which
are "dual-branded." The most common dual-branded card is a credit card that has both an American Express
logo and, for example, a bank logo (e.g. Bank of America, Wells Fargo, US Bank, etc.) These cards typically
include both the Amex brand and a debit brand (e.g. STAR, Pulse, NYCE, etc.)
The reason some cards are not supported and others are is determined by American Express and whether or not
they have granted specific BIN (Bank ID Number) range authority for the card to be used on a specific "alternative"
network. Typically, this includes the typical "dual-branded" cards, but we don't have any control over this, We have
to deal with what Amex has chosen to grant.

Here is a summary of what is working and what is not:
Supported (Dual-Branded Cards) in First Data and In Testing on TSYS.
>Amex/Discover cards (have only the Amex and Discover logos)
>Amex-branded cards (have only the Amex logo)
>Cards not dual-branded
Supported in First Data -- TSYS Lower Prority
> iPads
Not Yet Support - Schedule TBD
> Corporate Cards
> Purchasing Cards
> Gift Cards

Please note, the merchants themselves are not necessarily aware of the type of Amex cards that they are accepting
and whether or not they are processed/routed through the alternative debit networks. The PIN pads are designed
to make that determination automatically and to handle the transaction accordingly.

Also note that we do not control the pricing for these transactions, so there should be no expectation of reduced
processing costs.

Please let me know if you have any additional questions.

Thanks,
Randy
